The start symbol S can begin a derivation only through one of these two rules:

1. S → NT7 NT23  
2. S → NT97 NT54  

In Chomsky normal form each of the right-hand non-terminals must ultimately yield the first token of the generated string.

• NT7 has exactly one terminal production: NT7 → 't48'.  
  Therefore any string derived via rule 1 must start with the token t48.

• NT97 has only terminal productions: NT97 → 't31' | 't54'.  
  Therefore any string derived via rule 2 must start with t31 or t54.

The provided string, however, begins with the token t51.

Since neither NT7 nor NT97 can derive a string whose first symbol is t51, no derivation from S can produce the given string. Hence the string is not in the language generated by the grammar.

No

The grammar has only two possible productions for the start symbol S:

1. S → NT7 NT23  
   NT7 can produce only the single terminal t48.  
   Therefore every string derived via this rule must begin with t48.

2. S → NT97 NT54  
   NT97 produces exactly one terminal (t31 or t54), and NT54 produces exactly one terminal (t93, t12, or t53).  
   Hence any string derived via this rule has length 2.

The given string begins with t41 and has length 28, so it cannot be produced by either alternative:

• It does not start with t48, so it cannot come from S → NT7 NT23.  
• It is far longer than 2 tokens, so it cannot come from S → NT97 NT54.

Consequently, the grammar cannot generate the provided string.

2. S → NT97 NT54

   Therefore any string derived via this rule is of length 2 and must start with t31 or t54.

The string to be checked begins with t25, has length 43, and does not start with t48, t31, or t54. Consequently it cannot be generated by either of the only two possible derivations from S.

Hence the given grammar does not generate the provided string.

In this grammar the start symbol S can expand only in one of two ways:

1) S → NT7 NT23  
   NT7 produces exactly the single terminal ‘t48’.

2) S → NT97 NT54  
   NT97 produces exactly one terminal, either ‘t31’ or ‘t54’.

Whichever alternative is used, the very first terminal symbol generated by the grammar must therefore be one of

• t48   (from NT7)  
• t31   (from NT97)  
• t54   (from NT97)

The given string begins with the terminal t41.  
Since t41 cannot be the first symbol generated by either possible first non-terminal, the string cannot be derived from S under this grammar.
